cs.CR, cs.LG, cs.AI, cs.SE, cs.CV 

This paper is about developing methods for robust detection of malware using adversarial deep learning. The primary focus is on the security aspect of the problem, which suggests that the paper belongs to the cs.CR (Cryptography and Security) sub-category. The paper also involves the use of machine learning techniques, specifically SVM and neural networks, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. Additionally, the paper introduces methods for generating adversarial examples in the binary domain, which could fall under the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. The paper also involves the evaluation of the methods on a set of Portable Execution (PE) files, which suggests that it could belong to the cs.SE (Software Engineering) sub-category. Finally, the paper mentions the use of saddle-point optimization formulations, which are commonly used in computer vision, suggesting that it could also belong to the cs.CV (Computer Vision) sub-category.
